   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3187_1.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <address rend="letterhead">
                  <addrLine>3 Sussex Place</addrLine>
                  <addrLine>Lancaster Gate, W.2</addrLine>
               </address>
               <dateline>Sunday</dateline>
               <dateline><date when="1920-11-21">Nov 21/20</date>--&gt;</dateline>
               <salute>My dear friend – </salute>
            </opener>

            <p>I think you must have felt <hi rend="underline">pleasure</hi> in having written that
               very fine poem? There is so <hi rend="underline">much</hi> in it – one has to read it
               often -</p>

            <p>I read it aloud several times to <persName ref="#ps:MrsBlake">M<hi rend="superscript"
                     >rs</hi> Blake</persName> &amp; <persName ref="#ps:AnnaHirschmann"
                  >Anna</persName>, – who both had the good sense &amp; intelligence to appreciate
               it – I think the <subst><del>ve</del><add place="superimposed">st</add></subst>anzas
               that appeal <pb n="2" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3187_2.jpg"/> to me most are 5-6 8. &amp; 9 –
               The concluding lines of 5 are lovely – &amp; <hi rend="underline">8</hi> is a
               beautiful stanza. I am so grateful to you for mentioning the dear horses –.</p>

            <p>There is as much in 2 or 3 lines of this poem – as in a complete one by many people –
               I should think, isn't there?</p>

            <pb n="3" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3187_3.jpg"/>

            <p>I am hoping to hear that <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">Florence</persName> will
               come &amp; stay here for a day or night – &amp; see <unclear><persName
                     ref="#ps:MrHarsaut">Mr Harsaut</persName></unclear>? –</p>

            <p>The <persName ref="#ps:EdmundGosse">Gosse</persName> ceremony was a great success.
                  <persName ref="#ps:ArthurJamesBalfour">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>
                  Balfour</persName>'s speech, –(though I believe he had risen from a sick bed), was
               admirable, &amp; my brother's was very humorous. – A great many people turned up; but
               perhaps the room <add place="above">or the light</add> made them look their worst –.
               I thought they were, physically, a <hi rend="underline">very plain</hi> audience,
               although no doubt bubbling over with intelligence!</p>

            <pb n="4" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3187_4.jpg"/>

            <p>The <persName ref="#ps:JohnDrinkwater">John Drinkwater</persName>s (whom I met at a
               pleasant luncheon given by <persName ref="#ps:LucyClifford"> M<hi rend="superscript"
                     >rs</hi> Clifford</persName>) stood out as being good-looking. He spoke with
               great enthusiasm about <hi rend="underline">you</hi> –. I daresay you think well of
               some of his verse? –</p>

            <p>I went <add place="above">not long ago</add>to hear <persName ref="#ps:HenryNewbolt"
                  >Sir Henry Newbolt</persName> lecture on <persName ref="#ps:WalterdelaMare">M<hi
                     rend="superscript">r</hi> de la Mare</persName>. It was a charming address,
               &amp; he read a well chosen number of <unclear>the</unclear> poems, showing <persName
                  ref="#ps:WalterdelaMare">de la M.</persName> in his different moods. After the
               lecture – I, – (in a pushing manner–) forced myself on <persName
                  ref="#ps:HenryNewbolt">Sir Henry</persName>'s acquaintance, &amp; <pb n="5"
                  facs="uoedh_hl_h.3187_5.jpg"/> we, also, talked about you. I think from what he
               said, he will give another lecture on <hi rend="underline">your</hi> poetry. I hope
               so. -</p>

            <p>I hope you thoroughly enjoyed your <placeName ref="#pl:Dorchester"
                  >Dorchester</placeName> plays? I saw an account in 1 or 2 papers -. Have you had
               any more guests lately at <placeName ref="#pl:MaxGate">Max Gate</placeName>?</p>

            <p>I am sorry this great cold has come on <pb n="6" facs="uoedh_hl_h.3187_6.jpg"/> so
               early. I <hi rend="underline">hate</hi> the winter in <placeName ref="#pl:London"
                  >London</placeName>, on account of the slippery streets for the horse traffic –. I
               think some of ones <hi rend="underline">distresses</hi> get more acute as one grows
               older –, unfortunately.</p>

            <p>Best love to <persName ref="#ps:FlorenceHardy">F</persName>.</p>

            <closer>
               <salute><choice><abbr>Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</abbr>
                     <expan>Your</expan></choice>
                  <choice><abbr>affec</abbr>
                     <expan>affectionate</expan></choice> friend</salute>
               <signed>Flo H–</signed>
            </closer>

            <postscript>
               <p>
                  <unclear>
                     <hi rend="underline">Ps</hi>
                  </unclear>
               </p>
               <p>I fear the Nobel prize <hi rend="underline">has</hi> been given to a Scandinavian
                  – hasn't it?</p>
            </postscript>

         </div>
